  <div class="article-content" itemprop="articleBody">
    <p>
      Some imagine “logic” as a cold apparatus—good for mathematics, out of place in prayer, prophecy, and worship.
      But Scripture presents the God of Israel as faithful, consistent, and truthful. If that is so, then the world He made and the word He speaks
      will bear the marks of coherence. To ask whether Scripture and logic are compatible is to ask whether God is consistent with Himself.
      The prophetic books, the teaching of Jesus, and the writings of the apostles answer with a resounding yes.<span class="footnote-ref" id="ref-fn1"><sup><a href="#fn1">1</a></sup></span>
    </p>

    <h2>What We Mean by “Logic”</h2>
    <p>
      By logic we mean the basic commitments that make meaningful speech possible: identity (things are what they are), non-contradiction
      (a claim and its negation cannot both be true in the same sense at the same time), and the excluded middle (between a claim and its negation there is no third option that preserves truth).
      These are not sterile rules imposed on the Bible; they are the ordinary grammar of truthful discourse. When Scripture says God is faithful,
      it assumes a world where truth holds together rather than dissolving into contradiction.<span class="footnote-ref" id="ref-fn2"><sup><a href="#fn2">2</a></sup></span>
    </p>

    <h2>Reading Scripture with Coherence</h2>
    <p>
      The Bible is not a heap of slogans. It is a canon—a rule—whose parts interpret one another. Genealogies connect persons and promises.
      Laws form a moral architecture. Prophetic oracles presuppose covenant history. Wisdom literature articulates patterns of cause and effect.
      The Gospels arrange words and works to show identity and mission. The letters reason from claims to consequences. To read Scripture is to track
      claims, contexts, and conclusions. That is a logical task before it is an academic one.<span class="footnote-ref" id="ref-fn3"><sup><a href="#fn3">3</a></sup></span>
    </p>

    <h2>Prophetic Reasoning: From Absurdity to Clarity</h2>
    <p>
      The prophets did more than announce judgment and hope—they reasoned. Consider how they exposed idolatry. A craftsman fells a tree,
      burns part for heat, and carves the rest into a god. Then he bows down to the product of his own hands. The prophet’s point is not mere sarcasm—it is reductio ad absurdum:
      reduce a practice to its logical steps and its contradiction with reality becomes plain. In the same tradition, a prophet will contrast
      covenant commands with public behavior—weights and measures, courts and markets, harvest and sabbath—to show that a people cannot claim covenant fidelity
      while practicing systematic injustice. The contradiction collapses the claim.<span class="footnote-ref" id="ref-fn4"><sup><a href="#fn4">4</a></sup></span>
    </p>
    <p>
      Prophets also use analogical and a fortiori (“how much more”) reasoning. If a shepherd cares for a single lamb, how much more should leaders
      care for the flock? If a house built on sand collapses in wind, how much more a society built on lies? Such arguments are not ad hoc.
      They move from shared premises—what everyone can see—to piercing moral conclusions. This is logic in service of covenant truth.
    </p>

    <h2>Jesus’ Logic: Distinctions, Parables, and Consequences</h2>
    <p>
      Jesus’ teaching brims with logical clarity. When pressed on conflicting obligations, He draws distinctions that preserve categories:
      what belongs to the civil authority is not identical with what belongs to God. That is a logical division guarding the integrity of worship.
      When accused of breaking a rule by healing, He argues from lesser to greater: if an ordinary mercy is permitted, how much more an act that restores life and dignity?
      He exposes faulty inferences (“You nullify the commandment of God by your tradition”) and reveals hidden premises (treasure and heart move together).
      His parables are carefully structured analogies that invite hearers to carry a pattern from an everyday domain (farming, commerce, households) into the realm of the kingdom.
      The parable does not replace logic; it <em>embeds</em> logic in a story so that truth is grasped not only by the head but by the heart.<span class="footnote-ref" id="ref-fn5"><sup><a href="#fn5">5</a></sup></span>
    </p>

    <h2>Apostolic Argument: Step-by-Step Reasoning</h2>
    <p>
      The apostles write like advocates. They pose questions, answer objections, distinguish law and promise, compare covenants, and reason from premise to conclusion.
      One classic pattern proceeds in steps: all stand under sin; law reveals guilt rather than erasing it; God’s righteousness is revealed apart from law;
      therefore, boasting is excluded and faith unites Jew and Gentile. Even where the prose is pastoral, the backbone is argumentative: <em>if… then… therefore</em>.
      The aim is not to win a debate but to ground a people in what is sound, so that comfort, correction, and hope rest on reasons rather than sentiment alone.<span class="footnote-ref" id="ref-fn6"><sup><a href="#fn6">6</a></sup></span>
    </p>

    <h2>Why Logic Matters for Faithfulness</h2>
    <p>
      When logic is sidelined, piety becomes vulnerable to manipulation. Shallow slogans stand in for tested truth. Contradictory claims flourish because no one asks whether they can stand together.
      The result is confusion—about God’s character, about human dignity, about justice and mercy. But when leaders and households practice coherent reading,
      contradictions are exposed, and the center holds. This is not a call to dry rationalism; it is a call to love God with the mind as well as the heart,
      and to honor neighbors by speaking truthfully and consistently.<span class="footnote-ref" id="ref-fn7"><sup><a href="#fn7">7</a></sup></span>
    </p>

    <h2>A Short Guide to Logical Reading</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>Track identity.</strong> Who is speaking? To whom? What covenant terms frame this passage? Identity keeps our categories honest.<br/>
      <strong>Refuse contradictions.</strong> If an interpretation makes Scripture deny itself, revisit your premises. God’s truth does not need a loophole.<br/>
      <strong>Honor context.</strong> Words live in sentences, paragraphs, and books. Bring near and far contexts into view before drawing conclusions.<br/>
      <strong>Follow consequences.</strong> Ask, “If this claim is true, what follows?” Good doctrine bears good fruit—consistency in worship, justice, and compassion.<br/>
      <strong>Compare Scripture with Scripture.</strong> Let the clear illuminate the difficult; let the whole canon discipline any single verse pressed into extreme service.<span class="footnote-ref" id="ref-fn8"><sup><a href="#fn8">8</a></sup></span>
    </p>

    <h2>Examples at Work: Prophets and Jesus</h2>
    <h3>Exposing False Worship</h3>
    <p>
      A prophet surveys a marketplace where scales are tampered with and the poor are priced like grain. He does not only say “this is wrong;” he reveals the contradiction:
      a people who recite covenant words but engineer exploitation deny the very God they claim. Identity (who God is; who His people are) and non-contradiction (you cannot love God and hate His image)
      combine to produce a moral verdict and a call to repent.<span class="footnote-ref" id="ref-fn9"><sup><a href="#fn9">9</a></sup></span>
    </p>

    <h3>Healing and the Weightier Matters</h3>
    <p>
      Jesus encounters a man in need on a sacred day. His opponents elevate a boundary rule over mercy. Jesus answers with a structured argument:
      if you would rescue an animal in a pit, how much more should a human being be restored? The premises appeal to shared practices (rescuing an animal), a recognized hierarchy (human life exceeds livestock),
      and the goodness of mercy. The conclusion exposes their inconsistency and restores the man. Logic serves compassion rather than competing with it.<span class="footnote-ref" id="ref-fn10"><sup><a href="#fn10">10</a></sup></span>
    </p>

    <h3>Render to Whom It Is Due</h3>
    <p>
      When challenged about allegiance, Jesus refuses a false dilemma by dividing categories. A coin bears an earthly image; a person bears the image of God.
      Tribute is one thing; worship is another. The argument is crisp: identify kinds, assign what belongs to each, and refuse the collapse of categories that would turn piety into politics or politics into piety.<span class="footnote-ref" id="ref-fn11"><sup><a href="#fn11">11</a></sup></span>
    </p>

    <h2>Answering Common Objections</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>“Logic is Western; the Bible is ancient Near Eastern.”</strong> Logic is not a regional invention but the ordinary grammar of truth and falsehood.
      Ancient Hebrew poetry uses parallelism that relies on consistent meaning; law codes presume stable categories; wisdom literature compares cause and effect.
      These are logical operations embedded in the Bible’s own forms.<span class="footnote-ref" id="ref-fn12"><sup><a href="#fn12">12</a></sup></span>
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>“Logic puts God in a box.”</strong> God transcends creatures; He does not contradict Himself. To say God cannot lie is not to shrink Him but to honor His holiness.
      Mystery exceeds our grasp; contradiction destroys meaning. The church lives by mystery (things too great for us) and rejects nonsense (things that cannot be true).<span class="footnote-ref" id="ref-fn13"><sup><a href="#fn13">13</a></sup></span>
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>“Faith, not argument, changes hearts.”</strong> Granted—but faith comes by hearing, and hearing requires intelligible, coherent speech.
      Prophets, Jesus, and apostles all argued because love seeks understanding. Sound reasons are not the whole of faith; they are the rails along which faith travels.<span class="footnote-ref" id="ref-fn14"><sup><a href="#fn14">14</a></sup></span>
    </p>

    <h2>Conclusion</h2>
    <p>
      Scripture and logic are not rivals. Logic names the simple commitments that make truth tellable: identity, non-contradiction, and consequence.
      The prophets wielded these tools to expose idols and defend justice. Jesus used them to free the trapped, unmask hypocrisy, and teach with power.
      The apostles reasoned carefully to anchor communities in hope. Because God is faithful, His word is coherent, and His people are called to think and live coherently.
      To embrace logic is to respect the God who speaks truly—and to love neighbors with truthful, consistent words and works.<span class="footnote-ref" id="ref-fn15"><sup><a href="#fn15">15</a></sup></span>
    </p>
  </div>

